"Svensen H., Planke S., Polozov A.G., Schmidbauer N., Corfu F., Podladchikov Y.Y., Jamtveit B.","Siberian gas venting and the end-Permian environmental crisis",2009,"Earth and Planetary Science Letters","277","3-4",,"490","500",,,10.1016/j.epsl.2008.11.015,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58149345483&partnerID=40&md5=5ec6fc5247ea2a32ba50bc4d4aa8b662","Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway; Volcanic Basin Petroleum Research (VBPR), Oslo Research Park, 0349 Oslo, Norway; Institute of Geology of Ore Deposits, Petrography, Mineralogy and Geochemistry, 119017 Moscow, Russian Federation; Norwegian Institute for Air Research, Kjeller, Norway; Dept. of Geosciences, University of Oslo, PO Box 1047 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway","Svensen, H., Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway; Planke, S., Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway, Volcanic Basin Petroleum Research (VBPR), Oslo Research Park, 0349 Oslo, Norway; Polozov, A.G., Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway, Institute of Geology of Ore Deposits, Petrography, Mineralogy and Geochemistry, 119017 Moscow, Russian Federation; Schmidbauer, N., Norwegian Institute for Air Research, Kjeller, Norway; Corfu, F., Dept. of Geosciences, University of Oslo, PO Box 1047 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway; Podladchikov, Y.Y., Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway; Jamtveit, B., Physics of Geological Processes (PGP), University of Oslo, PO Box 1048 Blindern, 0316 Oslo, Norway","The end of the Permian period is marked by global warming and the biggest known mass extinction on Earth. The crisis is commonly attributed to the formation of the Siberian Traps Large Igneous Province although the causal mechanisms remain disputed. We show that heating of Tunguska Basin sediments by the ascending magma played a key role in triggering the crisis. Our conclusions are based on extensive field work in Siberia in 2004 and 2006. Heating of organic-rich shale and petroleum bearing evaporites around sill intrusions led to greenhouse gas and halocarbon generation in sufficient volumes to cause global warming and atmospheric ozone depletion. Basin scale gas production potential estimates show that metamorphism of organic matter and petroleum could have generated &gt; 100,000 Gt CO2. The gases were released to the end-Permian atmosphere partly through spectacular pipe structures with kilometre-sized craters. Dating of a sill intrusion by the U-Pb method shows that the gas release occurred at 252.0 ± 0.4 million years ago, overlapping in time with the end-Permian global warming and mass extinction. Heating experiments to 275 °C on petroleum-bearing rock salt from Siberia suggests that methyl chloride and methyl bromide were significant components of the erupted gases. The results indicate that global warming and ozone depletion were the two main drivers for the end-Permian environmental crisis. We demonstrate that the composition of the heated sedimentary rocks below the flood basalts is the most important factor in controlling whether a Large Igneous Provinces causes an environmental crisis or not. We propose that a similar mechanism could have been responsible for the Triassic-Jurassic (~ 200 Ma) global warming and mass extinction, based on the presence of thick sill intrusions in the evaporite deposits of the Amazon Basin in Brazil. © 2008 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","end-Permian; gas venting; Siberian Traps; Tunguska Basin","Amazon basins; Atmospheric ozone depletions; Basin sediments; end-Permian; Environmental crises; Evaporite; Evaporites; Field works; Flood basalts; Gas productions; Gas releases; Greenhouse gasses; Heating experiments; Jurassic; Mass extinctions; Methyl bromides; Methyl chlorides; Organic matters; Ozone depletions; Permian periods; Pipe structures; Rock salts; Siberian Traps; Triassic; Tunguska Basin; Atmospheric chemistry; Basalt; Carbon dioxide; Chlorine compounds; Forestry; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Heating; Igneous rocks; Lead; Leakage (fluid); Military operations; Organic compounds; Ozone; Ozone layer; Petroleum deposits; Petroleum refineries; Pipe; Sedimentary rocks; Sedimentology; Gases; evaporite; experimental study; gas flow; gas production; global warming; igneous intrusion; large igneous province; mass extinction; ozone depletion; paleoclimate; paleoenvironment; Permian; sill; trigger mechanism; uranium-lead dating; venting; Eurasia; Siberia",,,,,,"Barker, C., Calculated volume and pressure changes during the thermal-cracking of oil to gas in reservoirs (1990) Aapg Bull.-Am. Assoc. Pet. Geol., 74, pp. 1254-1261; Bartley, J.K., Pope, M., Knoll, A.H., Semikhatov, M.A., Petrov, P.Y.U., A Vendian-Cambrian boundary succession from the northwestern margin of the Siberian Platform: stratigraphy, palaeontology, chemostratigraphy and correlation (1998) Geol. Mag., 135, pp. 473-494; Beerling, D.J., Harfoot, M., Lomax, B., Pyle, J.A., The stability of the stratospheric ozone layer during the end-Permain eruption of the Siberian Traps (2007) Philos. Trans.-Royal Soc., Math. Phys. Eng. Sci., 365, pp. 1843-1866; Berner, R.A., Examination of hypotheses for the Permo-Triassic boundary extinction by carbon cycle modeling (2002) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U. S. A., 99, pp. 4172-4177; Bowring, S.A., Erwin, D.H., Jin, Y.G., Martin, M.W., Davidek, K., Wang, W., U/Pb zircon geochronology and tempo of the end-Permian mass extinction (1998) Science, 280, pp. 1039-1045; Conesa, J.A., Marcilla, A., Caballero, J.A., Evolution of gases from the pyrolysis of modified almond shells: effect of impregnation with CoCl2 (1997) J. Anal. Appl. Pyrolysis, 43, pp. 59-69; Corfu, F., U-Pb age, setting and tectonic significance of the anorthosite-mangerite-charnoc